description: In the turbulent 2016 and 2020 elections, the White House effectively hinged on fewer than 78,000 votes across the three closest states. Eight years ago, Donald Trump — despite losing the popular vote by 2.1 points — prevailed by a cumulative raw vote margin of 77,744 votes across Michigan, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin. Four years ago, Joe Biden — despite winning the popular vote by 4.5 points — defeated Trump by a cumulative raw vote margin of 42,918 votes across Arizona, Georgia and Wisconsin.
